More zones, more mobs, more items = more fun.<br>
Really?<br>
Logging on to an alt this week, I was disheartened.<br>
<br>
You have entered Cazic Thule.<br>
Only person there.<br>
You have entered South Karana.<br>
Only person there. <br>
You have entered Nagafen's Lair.<br>
Only person there.<br>
You have entered Crystal Caverns.<br>
Only person there.<br>
You have entered Dalnir Crypt.<br>
Only person there.<br>
You have entered Kaesora<br>
Only person there.<br>
<br>
Is the ever increasing gaming content unbalancing the player base of EverQuest?<br>
Is it destroying THE game of Everquest? To interact with your fellow hunters, to talk, to group, to laugh? Has EverQuest become just one type of game? The high end game?<br>
To the casual person, more and more expansions mean the initiation of more and more players in to the world of EverQuest, but this just isn't so. Sure, sales increase, mainly to accomodate the existing player base, but obviously the player base increases in itself. But does it enough? <br>
To me, the expansions are just wearing the world thin. Where there were 12 people in Zone A, there will then be 6 people in Zone A, and then 6 people in the new Zone B. And so forth and so on.<br>
On top of that, it is increasingly clear that the bulk of players congreate towards the 'easy road' to 60. The outside route. <br>
So, board, let me know what you think. Does Verant need to concentrate on existing content, or keep on expanding, until it will take 10 zones to find another player, instead of 8. <p>Halo 57th Beguiler<br>
