<br>
That's a big part of the problem, but another part has more simply to do with the age of the game and the ratio of experienced to new players.  By and large, people who have already levelled to 60 the 'hard' way, in the first year and some that the game was out, quite understandably don't want to dungeon crawl their way up again with second and third (and beyond) alts.  Getting exp in outdoor zones is easy, folks who have already levelled up don't need the mid-level loot out of dungeons (or if they want it they can send their heavy hitter in to farm it, or buy it at rediculously low prices), and so why not relax and grind your way up to 50 pulling to the ledge in OT/DL etc?  <br>
<br>
So what happens when new players come into the game, and start trying to find out where the 'action' is, they find the vast majority of people at their level (but not level of game playing experience) in the outdoor zones, and so that is where they end up going for groups.  The situation has gradually progressed to the point that the ratio of new to experienced low level players is so low, that inexperienced players have a difficult time even *finding* each other, much less finding several folks of like minds who want to explore the game...<br>
<br>
Our little guild finally made it into Droga last weekend (after our detour to the burynai mining camp and Nurga last week).  It literally took us all night (10 pm to 6 am) to make the loop to the Chief room and back, but we had a fabulous time, 4 of the 8 people on the trip dinged, and we got some nice items (including a Shroud of Nature and a Goblin Backstabber).  They were all floored by the sheer size of the place and the great variety of casting mobs there; our necro nearly got the party wiped several times when she 'let' the pet get ahead of the party, but all in all we had a great time, and they learned a *lot*.  At one point, about 4 hours into the trip, our SK said: &quot;Wow, I wonder how many people even know this exists...&quot;.  She, and our necro, had *never* seen the inside of a dungeon before except for Paw when we found them, in their mid 30s, and they're both intelligent adults who interact well with others, but they had simply been going where the 'action' was... <br>
<br>
So the end result is that newer players to the game *don't* have the same experiences that those who came to the game when it was newer had, and have a harder and harder time finding people to interact with who aren't 'jaded' about the low-mid level game, just racing through it to get to where the 'real' game is, and disdainful of the quests and loot available at that level.  This gets communicated very quickly to younger players, who quickly adopt the same attitude.  I can't say that I know what the solution is, but clearly, just adding more (overwhelmingly outdoor) zones *isn't* it...<br>
<br>
I think the best solution that I have seen so far, which Verant tried this summer and then seems to have abandoned, is to have the existing zones have a 'history' and change over time, as was done with Lfay and befallen (and to a lesser extent to the karanas) over the summer.  The 'newspaper' concept was also a great one (which also appears to have died, there hasn't been a new paper out since Volume 7), providing clues to quests/changes to areas in the game. It may take some work, but the best way to keep the game fresh is to keep the zones fresh, and people coming back to them, wondering what is going to happen next, rather than isolating them more and more from each other...<br>
<br>
Finally, I never understood why Verant has had such a problem trying to control the issue of 'loot inflation' in the game.  The trivial loot code was an attempt to approach the issue ass-backwards, and after the horse had left the barn, as it were.<br>
<br>
Instead of trying to implement a trivial loot code, or making everything nodrop (although I like the fact that the best items are nodrop), the best way to eliminate runaway twinking is simply to require a character to be of an appropriate level to *equip* an item.  It's routinely done with text MUDs.  If the level of the character is far too low for that character to have contributed to the killing of the mob who drops/quests it, the item shouldn't 'proc':  'You do not possess the force of will to equip this item'.  Set the limit at 7 levels below the level of the mob in question (the point at which you cannot hit a mob with spells and are barely scratching it with weapons).  Voila! You have just put a huge dent in farming for twinks/cash, and low and mid level players will have something to look forward to again, as well as something of value to trade/sell down when they no longer need it.<br>
<br>
Of course, Halo, you are preaching to the choir here <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  I do wish there was a way to bring people together in the game in a meaningful way these days other than zerg scale raids.  I really enjoy taking a group of 6-10 people down into a hole in the ground for a night of spelunking, with the hope of having some surprizes along the way.  One of the few things that Verant appears to have done 'right' with this expansion is to create some high level zones that will allow for experienced players to continue the smaller scale game.  I just wish they would do something for the 'old world', and the newer players in it, to stimulate interest in the first 45-50 levels, else Verant is going to wake up one day and find that their wellspring of new players has dried up completely...<br>
<br>
